<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-108-022 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 968 158</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 9 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multimedia helps sell insurance in Toronto. (O'Hara Systemsinstalls computer-based kiosks to quote insurance rates)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   O'Hara Systems (Marketing).andO;Topic:     Multimedia technologyInsurance.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MULTIMEDIA HELPS SELL INSURANCE IN TORONTO 07/09/91 TORONTO, ONTARIO, CANADA,1991 JUL 9 (NB) -- Computers are selling insurance in a handful of Torontostores.andP;  A local firm, O'Hara Systems, has installed computer-based kiosks inseveral department stores and food stores that can quote insurance rates andin some cases sell policies.andM;The kiosks use multimedia -- interactive audio and video driven by a computer-- to answer questions and give price quotes.andP;  Each kiosk includes anIBM-compatible personal computer with a touch-sensitive screen, a videodiskplayer, and a laser printer that produces written price quotes.andP;  Some of thekiosks include credit-card readers so that they can actually sell policies.andO;Each one also includes a modem, so rate changes can be fed to the systemsremotely.andM;Frank O'Hara, president of O'Hara Systems, said multimedia makes the systemseasier to use than they would be if they relied on keyboard input andtext-only displays.andM;The kiosks have been installed in selected Sears department stores and FoodCity grocery stores in greater Toronto.andP;  They have been in place for aboutfour months, O'Hara said.andP;  Three insurance firms are involved with O'Hara inthe project.andM;(Grant Buckler/19910707/Press Contact: Frank O'Hara, O'Hara Systems,416-425-5550)</TEXT></DOC>